## 3. The 9 SpecKit Agents — What Each Does

Your `.github/agents/` directory has all 9 agents correctly in place:

| Agent | File Size | Role in Your Workflow |
|---|---|---|
| `speckit.clarify` | 11 KB | Pre-analysis Q&A — removes spec ambiguity BEFORE analyze |
| `speckit.analyze` | 7.6 KB | Writes EARS-format requirements to `.specify/features/{name}/requirements.md` |
| `speckit.specify` | 15.6 KB | Extended specification writing (detailed feature spec) |
| `speckit.plan` | 6.2 KB | Writes `plan.md` — method signatures, sequence diagrams |
| `speckit.tasks` | 9.2 KB | Breaks `plan.md` into atomic `tasks.md` checklist |
| `speckit.implement` | 10.4 KB | Reads `tasks.md`, generates code, marks items `[X]` |
| `speckit.checklist` | 17 KB | End-of-feature validation against all spec outputs |
| `speckit.constitution` | 5.5 KB | Sets up `.specify/memory/constitution.md` (project memory) |
| `speckit.taskstoissues` | 1.1 KB | Creates GitHub Issues from `tasks.md` |

**Correct ordering per feature:**
```
clarify → analyze → specify → plan → tasks → implement → checklist
```

> [!NOTE]
> `speckit.specify` (15.6 KB) is more thorough than `speckit.analyze` (7.6 KB). For complex features like `BookingStateMachineConfig` and `DistributedLockService`, use `speckit.specify`. For simpler CRUD features, `analyze → plan → tasks → implement` is sufficient.

